</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8AE96506FFEE6816FF4AF8B3CD55FE31" lastPageId="105" lastPageNumber="106" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C24C368DFFEE6817FF4AF8B3CE38F8FC" blockId="104.[189,303,1883,1909]" box="[189,303,1883,1909]" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
<heading id="990481E1FFEE6817FF4AF8B3CE38F8FC" bold="true" box="[189,303,1883,1909]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" reason="3">
<emphasis id="F087EA9FFFEE6817FF4AF8B3CE38F8FC" bold="true" box="[189,303,1883,1909]" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C24C368DFFEE6816FF4AF862CD55FE31" blockId="104.[189,1398,1930,2027]" lastBlockId="105.[189,1399,267,441]" lastPageId="105" lastPageNumber="106" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
<bibRefCitation id="A6624B7CFFEE6817FF4AF862CEE1F82C" author="Rauschert &amp; Arntz" box="[189,502,1930,1957]" firstAuthor="Rauschert" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" refId="ref143760" refString="Rauschert M. &amp; Arntz W. E. 2015. Antarctic Macrobenthos. A Field Guide of the Invertebrates Living at the Antarctic Seafloor: Arntz &amp; Rauschert Selbstverlag, Deichweg." type="book" year="2015">Rauschert &amp; Arntz (2015)</bibRefCitation>
do not indicate the coordinates of their ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="05F34D0EFFEE6817FC1DF863CBFEF82D" authorityName="Lorz &amp; Coleman in Lorz et al." authorityYear="2009" box="[1002,1257,1930,1956]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epimeriidae" genus="Epimeria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustoides">
<emphasis id="F087EA9FFFEE6817FC1DF863CBFEF82D" box="[1002,1257,1930,1956]" italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Epimeria robustoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
1’, but this information is given in an early draft of the book made available to the authors: ANT-XIX/5, LAMPOS, stn 229-1, Bruce Ridge. It is not known where the specimen is stored; in 
<date id="B64D104DFFEE6817FBC7F839CBE4F862" box="[1072,1267,2000,2027]" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" value="2015-11">November 2015</date>
, it was not deposited at the Berlin Museum (Coleman pers. com.).As its colour pattern, with large red patches, is very different from the purely white 
<taxonomicName id="05F34D0EFFEF6816FD68FED9CC2BFEC3" authority="Verheye, 2017" authorityName="d’Acoz &amp; Verheye" authorityYear="2017" box="[671,828,305,330]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epimeriidae" genus="Epimeria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gargantua" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="F087EA9FFFEF6816FD68FED9CC2BFEC3" box="[671,828,305,330]" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">E. gargantua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="EBB457E4FFEF6816FCB0FED9CCB2FEC2" box="[839,933,305,331]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
found more southernly, this specimen possibly belongs to a distinct species. It should be noted that the colour pattern of all 
<taxonomicName id="05F34D0EFFEF6816FB2EFEBECA61FEE6" authority="Verheye, 2017" authorityName="d’Acoz &amp; Verheye" authorityYear="2017" box="[1241,1398,342,367]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epimeriidae" genus="Epimeria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gargantua" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="F087EA9FFFEF6816FB2EFEBECA61FEE6" box="[1241,1398,342,367]" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">E. gargantua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="EBB457E4FFEF6816FF4AFE92CE0FFE1D" box="[189,280,378,404]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
collected during the cruises ANT-XXIII/8 and ANT-XXIX/3 (
<specimenCount id="D4F5FD04FFEF6816FC00FE92CB8DFE1D" box="[1015,1178,377,404]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" type="generic">20 specimens</specimenCount>
) was examined on board and exhibited no variation.
</paragraph>
